  "prompt": "Why do cats lick furniture?",
  "response": "Cats may lick furniture for several reasons:\n\n1. Marking territory\n- Cats have scent glands in their mouth and use licking as a way to mark objects as their own\n\n2. Stress or anxiety\n- Excessive licking can be a self-soothing behavior when cats feel nervous or anxious\n\n3. Compulsive behavior\n- Some cats develop compulsive licking habits similar to obsessive-compulsive disorder\n\n4. Taste or texture\n- The furniture might have an interesting taste or texture that attracts the cat\n- Residue from food, spills, or cleaning products could be appealing\n\n5. Nutrient deficiency\n- In rare cases, cats might lick objects due to a mineral deficiency\n\n6. Medical issues\n- Neurological problems or certain health conditions can cause excessive licking\n\n7. Grooming instinct\n- Cats naturally groom themselves and might extend this behavior to objects around them\n\nIf the licking becomes excessive or compulsive, it's best to consult a veterinarian to rule out underlying health issues and get professional advice.",
